Information that has been suggested to me online suggests that Ozempic and drugs like it are not safe and come with higher risks of more severe side effects. However, I have a sister who, for our whole lives (she is only 1 year older than me), has eaten the exact same diet as me, played the same sport as me, which she worked much harder at, and is a much more physically active person in general. Due to our genes she has a thyroid issue and only because of her do I understand that it is truly out of SOME people's control. It is not fair what she has to deal with and the stigmas that come with it. Stigma from people like me. And even knowing this I still think negatively of drugs like Ozempic, however I do not personally know anyone who has used or benefitted from a drug like that.

18 months ago I developed a small bowel stricture (from taking Aleve daily for years) I lost 20 pounds and recovered. I then gained the weight back 6 months later. I decided to see if I could lose the weight again, as it had felt good to be thinner. I started using an app, first "MyNetDiary" and then "Cronometer." I had had no idea how many calories were in the foods I'd been eating nor what amount I needed to eat to lose weight. The apps helped me TREMENDOUSLY to learn how to eat more carefully. Doing this and going to the gym twice a week for basic weight lifting, nothing extra, no cardio, just dog walking,  I was able to lose 38 pounds. I think most people could eat better and lose weight if they saw DAILY how many calories they are actually consuming and how many they SHOULD be consuming to first LOSE weight and then maintain it. I now can eat a few more calories as I don't need to lose more weight. The problem would be falling back into old eating habits, I LOVE sweets, so I continue to track my food daily to stay within a general range of calorie intake. People can take weight loss pills, that's fine but there are side effects to medication and it doesn't help them learn to understand they food they are eating.

Studies have shown that long term weight loss is physically impossible to maintain for the vast majority of people who lose weight, and that weight fluctuations are much harder on your heart than just being overweight or obese. Additionally, the BMI scale which is used to determine if someone is overweight or obese are based on an outdated system that was never based on health, but was based solely on what one man found attractive, in only white populations, and does not take into account race, genetics, or actual health or science. Until we change the outdated system that we are currently using, weight should not even remotely be considered a factor in a person's health, as health was not a factor when determining the original scale that we still use to day. Please stop spreading fatphobic messages regarding weight, such as the need to lose weight or that it is possible as long as you just control your hunger and have more self control by joining this support group! That's not how weight loss works. Weight loss doesn't work. And because there's no studies that even show it's possible, there's no studies that actually show that losing weight makes people healthier.
